  "base_commit": "85a60221a978c45bef1dea0894dd7287d9c12f4f",
  "pr_number": 299,
  "issue_number": 290,
  "issue_title": "Feature: define workflow file format with parameters and expected states",
  "issue_body": "## Problem\n\nThere is no structure for expressing a repeatable local workflow. A raw trace is a recording of what happened; a workflow needs to be a portable, parameterized, human-readable description of what should happen.\n\n## Proposed behavior\n\nDefine a workflow file schema (JSON or Markdown front matter + steps) that captures the step sequence, expected intermediate screen states, parameterized value slots, and per-step policy requirements. Add a parser and serializer so the replay engine and trace-capture path share the same model.\n\n## Goal to reach\n\nA serializable, inspectable workflow file can represent a successful trace as a replayable workflow, and a developer can author one by hand.\n\n## Minimal scope\n\n- Design the schema: steps, tool name + arguments, expected state predicates (screen text, element presence), parameter slots, and optional skill/tool scope.\n- Add `WorkflowDefinition` data class and a parser from JSON.\n- Add a serializer so a `WorkflowTrace` can be converted into a `WorkflowDefinition`.\n- Write schema documentation (add to `docs/`).\n\n## Out of scope\n\n- Replay engine.\n- Capture path (separate issue).\n- UI.\n\n## User workflow\n\nA developer inspects a saved workflow file and understands every step without needing to read source code.\n\n## Local-first impact\n\nWorkflow files live entirely on device. The schema should be simple enough to hand-edit.\n\n## Safety and security considerations\n\nThe schema must support expressing per-step policy requirements so the replay engine knows which steps need approval before execution.",
  "merged_at": "2026-06-19T14:05:04.000Z",
